# thedoc - git line-ending normalization
#
# Without this file, Windows clones with core.autocrlf=true (a common
# default) convert bash scripts to CRLF, which breaks heredocs and
# subtle end-of-line behaviors. Force LF for shell + Python + PS +
# markdown + YAML so the working tree matches what we authored
# regardless of the user's platform.
#
# .cmd files keep their default (which on Windows means CRLF after
# autocrlf-normalized checkout) - cmd.exe handles either fine but
# CRLF is the native convention.

# Default: LF for text. This is conservative; the file-type rules
# below tighten it for files where mismatch causes real bugs.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Bash/Python/PowerShell: CRLF in any of these breaks parsing or
# runtime behavior. Pin to LF.
*.sh   text eol=lf
*.py   text eol=lf
*.ps1  text eol=lf

# Markdown and YAML: tooling generally handles both, but consistency
# helps diffs across platforms.
*.md   text eol=lf
*.yml  text eol=lf
*.yaml text eol=lf

# cmd batch: leave default. cmd.exe on modern Windows handles LF,
# but the format is Windows-native and CRLF is the convention.
*.cmd  text

# ASCII art and other text resources: LF (matches our authoring).
*.txt  text eol=lf
